SIMPLE: flute
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flute
<hw>Flute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>floute</ets>,
<ets>floite</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>fla⟦uum⟧te</ets>, <ets>flahute</ets>,
<ets>flahuste</ets>, F. <ets>fl<?/te</ets>; cf. LL. <ets>flauta</ets>,
D. <ets>fluit</ets>. See <er>Flute</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A musical wind instrument, consisting of a hollow
cylinder or pipe, with holes along its length, stopped by the fingers or
by keys which are opened by the fingers. The modern flute is closed at
the upper end, and blown with the mouth at a lateral hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The breathing <qex>flute's</qex> soft notes are heard around.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A channel of curved section; --
usually applied to one of a vertical series of such channels used to
decorate columns and pilasters in classical architecture. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> under <er>Base</er>, <pos>n.</pos></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A similar channel or groove made in wood or other
material, esp. in plaited cloth, as in a lady's ruffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A long French breakfast roll.</def>
<rj><au>Simonds.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A stop in an organ, having a flutelike
sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Flute bit</b></col>, <cd>a boring tool for piercing
ebony, rosewood, and other hard woods.</cd> -- <col><b>Flute
pipe</b></col>, <cd>an organ pipe having a sharp lip or wind-cutter
which imparts vibrations to the column of air in the pipe.</cd>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Flute
<hw>Flute</hw> <pr>(fl⟦umac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>fl⟦ucir⟧te</ets> a transport, D. <ets>fluit</ets>.]</ety> <def>A
kind of flyboat; a storeship.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Armed en fl⟦ucir⟧te</b></col> <pr>(<?/)</pr>
<fld>(Nav.)</fld>, <cd>partially armed.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Flute
<hw>Flute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>flouten</ets>, <ets>floiten</ets>, OF. <ets>fla⟦uum⟧ter</ets>,
<ets>fle⟦uum⟧ter</ets>, <ets>flouster</ets>, F. <ets>fl⟦ucir⟧ter</ets>,
cf. D. <ets>fluiten</ets>; ascribed to an assumed LL.
<ets>flautare</ets>, <ets>flatuare</ets>, fr. L. <ets>flatus</ets> a
blowing, fr. <ets>flare</ets> to blow. Cf. <er>Flout</er>,
<er>Flageolet</er>, <er>Flatulent</er>.]</ety> <def>To play on, or as
on, a flute; to make a flutelike sound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Flute
<hw>Flute</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fluted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fluting</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To play,
whistle, or sing with a clear, soft note, like that of a
flute.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Knaves are men,⟦br⟧
That lute and <qex>flute</qex> fantastic tenderness.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The redwing <qex>flutes</qex> his o-ka-lee.</q>
<rj><qau>Emerson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form flutes or channels in, as in a column, a
ruffle, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flute a bec</ent>⟦br⟧
